# Part 1a. Produce scatter plot matrix.

# The following two functions are essentially the same as given
# on the help page for the pairs() function.
panel.hist <- function(x, ...)
{
  usr <- par("usr"); on.exit(par(usr))
  par(usr = c(usr[1:2], 0, 1.5) )
  h <- hist(x, plot = FALSE)
  breaks <- h$breaks; nB <- length(breaks)
  y <- h$counts; y <- y/max(y)
  rect(breaks[-nB], 0, breaks[-1], y, col = "cyan", ...)
}
panel.cor <- function(x, y, digits = 2, prefix = "", cex.cor, ...)
{
  usr <- par("usr"); on.exit(par(usr))
  par(usr = c(0, 1, 0, 1))
  r <- (cor(x, y)) # got rid of an absolute value here
  txt <- format(c(r, 0.123456789), digits = digits)[1]
  txt <- paste0(prefix, txt)
  if(missing(cex.cor)) cex.cor <- 0.8/strwidth(txt)
  text(0.5, 0.5, txt, cex = cex.cor * (abs(r)*.7+0.3))
  # modification on line above so that text for small correlations 
  # is not too small to read.
}

# Part 2a. The function mUnif() is given below.

mUnif <- function(n){
  if ( n<3 || length(n) !=1) 
    stop("n must be a scalar integer >2")
  m <- numeric(n)
  m[n] <- (0.5)^(1/n)
  m[1] <- 1-m[n]
  m[2:(n-1)] <- ((2:(n-1))-.3175)/(n+.365)
  m
}

# Part 2b.

# The function filCor() is given below.

filCor <- function(x){
  sortx <- sort(x)
  normqs <- qnorm(mUnif(length(x)))
  fcor <- cor(sortx,normqs)
  fcor
}

# Part 2d:

# Now for an enhanced version of filCor(). I'll call it filCorr().

# First, to get the p-value for the Filliben correlation coefficient
# I'll write a function specifically for that purpose call pFil().
# This function takes arguments fcor, the Filliben correlation
# for which we want a p-value; n, the length of the data vector that
# yielded the fcor value; and simsize, which could be supplied by
# the uder, but takes a default value of 100000. The function 
# generates simsize normally distributed vectors of length n, and puts
# them in the columns of an n x simsize matrix. Each column is
# sorted from smallest to largest and then each column's correlation
# with the median order statistics from a normal distribution is
# computed. Thus, we get simsize (e.g, 100000) Filliben correlations
# computed from truly normal data. These correlations are held in
# the vector filCorVec. The p-value is then computed as the proportion
# of the values in filCorVec that are smaller than fcor, the observed
# Filliben correlation coefficient. That p-value is returned by the 
# function pFil().

pFil <- function(fcor,n,simsize=1e+05){
  normVec <- rnorm(n*simsize)
  normMat <- matrix(normVec[order(rep(1:simsize,each=n),normVec)],nrow=n,ncol=simsize,
                    byrow=FALSE)
  filCorVec <- array(cor(normMat, qnorm(mUnif(n))))
  p <- sum(filCorVec<fcor)/simsize
  p
}

# Now for the enhanced version of filCor:

filCorr <- function(x,plotit=FALSE,pval=FALSE,...){
  # First compute the Filliben corr as before:
  sortx <- sort(x)
  normqs <- qnorm(mUnif(length(x)))
  fcor <- cor(sortx,normqs)
  # If requested compute the p-value.
  if (pval){
    p <- pFil(fcor,length(x))
  }
  # if requested, plot a Filliben Q-Q plot and include the test
  # stat and p-value as text in the upper left corner of the plot.
  # The function supplies the xlabel (xlab) but ylab, main, and other
  # graphical parameters can be supplied to filCorr() and they will
  # be passed along to qqplot(), which does the plotting.
  if (plotit){
    qqplot(normqs,sortx,xlab="Normal quantiles",...)
    qqline(sortx)
    if (pval)
      legend("topleft",
             legend=c(paste("Filliben cor =",round(fcor,5)),
                      paste("p =",round(p,4))),
             bty="n")
    else 
      legend("topleft",legend=paste("Filliben cor =",round(fcor,5)),
             bty="n")
  }
  # If a pvalue was requested return both the correlation and its 
  # p-value
  if (pval){
    return( list(fcor=fcor,pval=p))
  } # Otherwise return jsut the correlation.
  else return( list(fcor=fcor))
}

# This ends the assignment. However, given the code that I wrote 
# above to generate p-values, it is not hard to write a function
# that computes critical values for the Filliben correlation 
# coefficient like those given in Table 1 of Filliben's paper.
# The function is given below. It is called critFil(). For a given
# n (length of the data vector), it will compute critical values
# corresponding to each of several alpha-values (supplied in the
# vector alphas) based on a simulation of size simsize. The
# default is to use a simulaation size of 100000 and to compute
# criical values at alapha = .01, .025, .05, .1, and .5.

critFil <- function(n,alphas=c(.01,.025,.05,.1,.5),simsize=1e+05){
  normVec <- rnorm(n*simsize)
  normMat <- matrix(normVec[order(rep(1:simsize,each=n),normVec)],nrow=n,ncol=simsize,
                    byrow=FALSE)
  filCorVec <- array(cor(normMat, qnorm(mUnif(n))))
  qvec <- quantile(filCorVec,probs=alphas)
  qvec
}
